The National Commission for Protection of Child Rights (NCPCR) Tuesday issued an order to the District Magistrate of South East Delhi to identify the children involved in Shaheen Bagh protests and send them for counselling. In its order, the NCPCR said the children â€œmay suffer from mental traumaâ€ because of â€œrumours and miscommunicationâ€ regarding the CAA.

â€œWe issued the order Tuesday. This order is based on viral videos, which show children saying things like â€˜Pradhan Mantri humko desh se nikal denge (the Prime Minister will throw us out of the country)â€™, and â€˜Home Minister ko kaagaz nahi dikhayenge toh who humein detention camp mein bhej denge (if we donâ€™t show documents to the Home Minister, he will send us to detention camps)â€™. This is the effect of rumours regarding CAA. For the children to be affected by this and say things like this is extremely worrying. We believe the children are in need of intense counselling. If need be, their parents should also be sent for counselling,â€ said chairperson NCPCR Priyank Kanoongo.

Kanoongo added that it is apparent the children have suffered from deep trauma because of the â€œrumours floating aroundâ€. He said local counselling centres are available to this end. The NCPCR has taken cognizance of the matter under Section 13 of the CPCR Act, 2005.

â€œIn view of the seriousness of the issue and its impact on the children, you are requested to issue necessary directions to DCPO along with Police Child Welfare Officer/SJPU to identify these children and arrange counselling session for them and also for their parents, if deemed fit. Further, if required, these children may be produced before the CWC,â€ states the order.

The District Magistrate is to submit a report to the NCPCR within 10 days.

